{{Infobox person | name = Abdullah Hakim Quick | image = | caption = | residence = Canada | birth_place = Cambridge, Massachusetts | nationality = | education = | alma_mater = | home_town = | death_date = | occupation = Teacher, Historian, Imam | title = | spouse = | parents = | children = | website = | footnotes = }}
'''Abdullah Hakim Quick''' (born June 25, 1949) is an [[imam]], [[historian]] and travelling lecturer from [[North America]].
== Background == He was born in the [[United States of America]]. He is of [[African Americans|African American]], [[Caribbean people|Caribbean]] and [[Mohawk people|Mohawk]] ([[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]]) descent. He was born in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]] and grew up in [[Boston]].<ref name="Globe2">{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/toronto/meet-the-toronto-imam-wanted-dead-by-islamic-state/article29809829/| title=Meet the Toronto imam wanted dead by Islamic State|newspaper=The Globe and Mail|date=April 29, 2016}}</ref> He converted to Islam in [[Canada]] in 1970.{{citation needed|date=July 2016}}
He received a [[Bachelor's Degree]] from the [[Islamic University of Madinah]] in 1979. He was one of the first two students from the west and the first American to have done so and receive an [[Ijazah]]. He received a [[Master's Degree]] and [[Ph.D|PhD]] from the [[University of Toronto]].<ref name="upenn.edu">{{Cite web|url=http://www.africa.upenn.edu/Articles_Gen/Uthm_Fodio.html|title=An Interview on Uthman dan Fodio|website=www.africa.upenn.edu|access-date=2016-08-18}}</ref> His thesis was an analysis of the life and writings of Sheikh ‘Uthman Dan Fodio, a great West African Scholar, [[warrior]], and social activist.<ref name="upenn.edu"/>{{citation needed|date=July 2016}}
== Career == Over the past four decades Quick has travelled to 61 countries where he lectured at universities, mosques and at public events.<ref name="almaghrib.org">{{Cite web|url=http://almaghrib.org/instructors/abdullah-hakim-quick#profile|title=AlMaghrib Institute {{!}} Our Instructors {{!}} Shaykh Abdullah Hakim Quick|website=almaghrib.org|access-date=2016-08-18}}</ref> He has also served as an [[imam]], teacher, counsellor and media consultant in the USA, Canada, South Africa and the West Indies.<ref name="almaghrib.org"/> He is currently senior lecturer with the [[Islamic Institute of Toronto]] (I.I.T.)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.islamicinstitute.ca/Instructor-Bio.aspx?i=23|title=Islamic Institute of Toronto|website=www.islamicinstitute.ca|access-date=2016-08-18}}</ref> and the outreach coordinator with the Canadian Council of Imams.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.canadiancouncilofimams.com/contact-us/|title=Contact Us|website=www.canadiancouncilofimams.com|access-date=2016-08-18}}</ref> He is also the history department head and a lecturer at [[AlMaghrib Institute]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://almaghrib.org/instructors/abdullah-hakim-quick#profile|title=AlMaghrib Institute|website=almaghrib.org}}</ref>
==Recognition== In recognition of the contribution he has made to Canada, Quick has received the [[Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Medal]].<ref name="Globe2"/>
==Threats== Quick was listed in ISIS's hit list on an issue of Dabiq, with ISIS encouraging his death.<ref>"Kill the Imams of the West" (PDF). Dabiq 1437 Rajab (April - May 2016). Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant (14): 13–14</ref>
