931850-200-asias-mysterious-role-in-the-early-origins-of-humanity}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Li |first1=T |title=New Middle Pleistocene hominid crania from Yunxian in China |journal=Nature |volume=357 |issue=6377 |pages=404–407 |date=Jun 4, 1992 |doi=10.1038/357404a0|bibcode=1992Natur.357..404T }}</ref> Evidence of use of [[fire]] ([[Daughters of Jacob Bridge]], [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]]).<ref>[https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn4944-charred-remains-may-be-earliest-human-fires.html "Charred remains may be earliest human fires"], ''New Scientist'', April 29, 2004.</ref> [[Brunhes–Matuyama reversal|Brunhes–Matuyama geomagnetic reversal]].<!--779 ka BC--> Hominins present in [[Luzon]], Philippines, possible ancestors of Flores man.<!--707 ka BC--><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Colin Barras |title=Bones may reveal origin of hobbits |journal=New Scientist |date=May 12, 2018 |url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg23831773-200-ancient-humans-in-philippines-may-have-given-rise-to-hobbits}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=T. Ingicco et al. |title=Earliest known hominin activity in the Philippines by 709 thousand years ago |journal=Nature |volume=557 |issue=7704 |pages=233–237 |date=May 2, 2018 |doi=10.1038/s41586-018-0072-8|pmid=29720661 }}</ref> ''[[Homo floresiensis]]''-like creatures on [[Flores]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Mystery human hobbits ruled tiny Asian island 700,000 years ago|journal=New Scientist|date=Jun 11, 2016|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg23030773-100}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author1=Gerrit van den Bergh|author2=''et al.''|title=''Homo floresiensis''-like fossils from the early Middle Pleistocene of Flores|journal=Nature|date=Jun 2016|doi=10.1038/nature17999|volume=534|issue=7606|pages=245–248|pmid=27279221|bibcode=2016Natur.534..245V}}</ref><!--700 ka BC--> |- | align=center |700 ka – 550 ka || [[Günz glaciation]] || [[Yellowstone Caldera]] [[supervolcano]] spreads [[Lava Creek Tuff|ash over North America]].<!--630 ka--> 